Artificial lighting provides an indispensable energy service (illumination) for modern life. 
The field of societal exergy analysis considers light (and many other energy products)
to be enablers of economic growth, and 
lighting contributes a small, but non-negligible fraction of total useful exergy
input to modern economies.
In societal exergy analyses, 
the exergetic efficiency of lamps has been approximated by an energy efficiency, 
resulting in much confusion to date. 
In response, 
we use recent results from the photometry and thermodynamics of radiation literatures to
develop a new, exact method for calculating the exergy of light and the exergetic efficiency of lamps.
The exact method 
(a)~is free of (possibly erroneous) assumptions for the maximum luminous efficacy, 
(b)~uses the correct spectral exergy-to-energy ratio, no longer assuming its value to be 1, and
(c)~allows choices for the spectral weighting function.
The exact method exposes assumptions inherent to the original method and 
leads to a better approximation of lamp exergetic efficiency, when needed.
To conclude, we provide two recommendations 
for societal exergy analysts:
(a)~use the new, exact method and the universal luminosity weighting function 
    when lamp spectral power distribution data are available and
(b)~use a reasonable approximation to the exact method when only lamp luminous efficacy data are available.
