%------------------------------
\subsubsection{Lamps}
\label{sec:lamps}
%------------------------------

To demonstrate how the spectral weighting function~($f_\lambda$)
affects the energy and exergy efficiency of lamps, 
we need both weighting functions (Section~\ref{sec:weighting_functions}) and
example lamps.

We obtained spectral power distributions of the lamps in Table~\ref{tab:lamps} from the 
Light Spectral Power Distribution Database (LSPDD)~\cite{Roby, miguel2017, aube2013}. 
The data in the LSPDD are provided 
in terms of \emph{relative intensity} ($\dot{E}_{EM,\lambda,rel}$) 
as opposed to \emph{absolute intensity} ($\dot{E}_{EM,\lambda}$).
Because lamps in the LSPDD are not measured using an integration sphere,
the integral of the spectral power distribution may not match the radiant power of the lamp
reported by the manufacturer.
To ensure that the integral of each lamp's spectral power distribution 
matches its reported radiant power, 
we applied the standard procedure of scaling the spectral power distribution 
by the ratio ($\mu$) of
the radiant power given by the manufacturer~($K \dot{W}_{elect,1}$) and  
the integral of the spectral radiant power taken from the relative intensity data~($\dot{E}_{EM,rel}$).
%
\begin{equation} 
  \mu \equiv \frac{K \dot{W}_{elect,1}}{\dot{E}_{EM,rel}} \; .
\end{equation}

We then applied the scaling factor~($\mu$) to the spectral power distribution data for each lamp, 
yielding a corrected spectral power distribution data~($\dot{E}_{EM,\lambda}$) for each lamp 
that matches the manufacturer's reported radiant power. 
%
\begin{equation} 
  \dot{E}_{EM,\lambda}  = \mu \dot{E}_{EM,\lambda,rel}
\end{equation}

Although the corrected spectral power distribution data were used for all analyses,
we later display (Figure~\ref{fig:wfs_and_lamps})
normalized spectral power distributions for each lamp,
such that the peak of each spectral power distribution is 1.
This normalizing process allows easy visual comparison 
of lamps with varying electricity consumption 
and spectral power distribution profiles.

We selected one representative lamp for each of four common lamp technologies
(incandescent, INC;
high pressure sodium, HPS;
compact fluorescent, CFL; and
light emitting diode, LED), 
each with a unique spectral power distribution.
See Table~\ref{tab:lamps} for details about lamps discussed throughout this paper.

