%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Comparison with previous approach 
            to calculating exergetic efficiency~($\eta_{X,L,v}$) 
            in societal exergy analysis}
\label{sec:compwithSEA}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

The method for calculating the exergy of light presented in Section~\ref{sec:phi_light}
differs from the previous approach used in the societal exergy analysis community.
This section
%
\begin{enumerate*}[label={(\alph*)}]
	
  \item characterizes the previous approach to calculating the exergy of light
        as an approximate method and 
        characterizes the new method for calculating the exergy of light presented in Section~\ref{sec:phi_light}
        as an exact method and
  
  \item evaluates the approximate method relative to the exact method 
        to obtain three implications for societal exergy analysis.
    
\end{enumerate*}


%------------------------------
\subsubsection{Approximate and exact methods} 
\label{sec:previous_approach}
%------------------------------

In societal exergy analysis, exergy calculations are sometimes hampered when 
``the useful output cannot or is not typically measured in energy units''
\cite[p.~17]{Sousa2017}. 
In these circumstances, researchers in societal exergy analysis approximate
exergetic efficiency by the quotient of
the minimum energy required to produce a given output and
the actual energy required to produce the same given output.
(See Section~\ref{sec:divergent_approaches}.)
This approximate method has been recommended
for lighting, sound, and information~\cite[p.~17]{Sousa2017}.

For lighting,
the approximate method involves the quotient of
the theoretical minimum rate of energy required to emit one lumen and
the actual rate of energy used to emit one lumen 
for a given lamp, where
the minimum and actual energy rates are obtained 
by taking the inverses of luminous efficacy~($K$).
For a lamp, the quotient is between the lamp's luminous efficacy~($K$)
and the maximum luminous efficacy~($K_{max}$).
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:K_over_e_max}
  \eta_{X,L,v} \approx \frac{\; \; \frac{1}{K_{max}} \; \; }{\frac{1}{K}}
       = \frac{K}{K_{max}} \; .
\end{equation}

Equation~\ref{eq:lum_effic_def} shows that 
the luminous efficacy of a lamp~($K$) is equal to the quotient
of the luminous power ($\Phi_{pl}$, Equation~\ref{eq:lumen}), expressed in lumens, and
the electricity consumption rate of the device
($\dot{W}_{elect,1}$ in Figure~\ref{fig:lamp}).
Substituting Equation~\ref{eq:lum_effic_def} into Equation~\ref{eq:K_over_e_max} gives
(with reference to Figure~\ref{fig:lamp})
exergetic efficiency for the approximate method:
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:prev_eta_X_v_light}
  \eta_{X,L,v} \approx \frac{ \; \; \frac{(683 \text{ lm/W}) \int V_\lambda \dot{E}_{EM,\lambda,3} \, \mathrm{d}\lambda}{\dot{W}_{elect,1}} \; \;}{K_{max}} \; .
\end{equation}


With recent advances in photometry (Section~\ref{sec:phi_light}),
it is now possible to determine the energy and exergy of light exactly, 
thereby relieving societal exergy analysts
of the need to approximate exergetic efficiency
by the quotient of
the minimum energy required to produce a lumen and
the actual energy required to produce a lumen.
Thus, we can evaluate the approximate method in light of recent advances, 
using exergetic efficiency as the point of comparison.

Comparing Equation~\ref{eq:prev_eta_X_v_light} (the approximate method)
to Equation~\ref{eq:eta_X_v_light} (the exact method)
reveals that the approximate method for calculating the exergetic efficiency of lighting
is correct only under the following conditions:
%
\begin{enumerate}[label={(\alph*)}]
	
  \item the maximum luminous efficacy ($K_{max}$) is assumed to be 683~lm/W, and 

  \item $\phi_{L,\lambda} = 1$ for all wavelengths,

  \item the spectral weighting function is taken to be the photopic luminosity function ($f_\lambda = V_\lambda$).

\end{enumerate}

As can be seen by comparing the luminous efficiency row of Table~\ref{tab:lamps} 
and the photopic luminosity row of Table~\ref{tab:results_etas},
final-to-useful efficiencies calculated using the photopic luminosity function~($\eta_{E,v,pl}$, Equation \ref{eq:eta_E_v_light} (with $f_\lambda = V_\lambda$)
are equivalent to luminous efficiency values
~(Equation~\ref{eq:prev_eta_X_v_light}) 
when maximum luminous efficacy~($K_{max}$) is taken to be 683~lm/W.


%------------------------------
\subsubsection{Implications for societal exergy analysis} 
\label{sec:implications_for_sea}
%------------------------------

The above comparison between the previous approximate method (Section~\ref{sec:previous_approach}) and
the new exact method of Section~\ref{sec:light_efficiency}
raises three implications for societal exergy analysis.

First, with the previous approximate method, 
the analyst was required to select a value for maximum luminous efficacy ($K_{max}$), 
the denominator of Equation~\ref{eq:prev_eta_X_v_light}.
The choice of $K_{max}$ can make a significant difference to the results.
The correct value for $K_{max}$ is 683~lm/W, 
because the approximate method relies upon luminous efficacy of lamps.
Many authors assume $K_{max} = 400 \text{ lm/W}$ 
(e.g., \citet{Ayres2005} and \citet{Guevara2016}),
thereby incorrectly overestimating exergetic efficiency of lighting~($\eta_{X,L,v}$)
by a factor of $\frac{683 \text{ lm/W}}{400 \text{ lm/W}} = 1.71$.

Second, to obtain the correct exergetic efficiency of lighting, 
analysts must reject the assumption of the previous approximate method that $\phi_{L,\lambda} = 1$.
Recent progress in photometry enables this rejection, 
following the methods of Section~\ref{sec:phi_light}.
Specifically, the spectral exergy-to-energy ratio of light ($\phi_{L,\lambda}$)
of Equation~\ref{eq:phi_L_lambda_shan_zhou} and Figure~\ref{fig:wfs_and_lamps} should be used.
We note, however, that $\phi_{L,\lambda}$ is close to~1 for all wavelengths of interest to illumination.
Happily, the previous approximate method was not far wrong to assume $\phi_L = 1$.

Third, in the approximate method, 
the analyst is required to use the photopic luminosity function~($V_\lambda$)
for the specular weighting function~($f_\lambda$).
However, it is not certain that the photopic luminosity function
is the best choice, 
as discussed in Section~\ref{sec:blue_light} below.

In summary, the exact method provides the following benefits over the approximate method:
%
\begin{enumerate}[label={(\alph*)}]
	
  \item it uses the correct spectral exergy-to-energy ratio~($\phi_{L,\lambda}$), no longer assuming its value to be~1;

  \item it is free of (possibly erroneous) assumptions for the maximum luminous efficacy ($K_{max}$); and 
  
  \item it allows choices for the spectral weighting function~($f_\lambda$), 
        no longer requiring $f_\lambda = V_\lambda$, 
        thereby enabling analyses suited precisely to each application of EM radiation
        (illumination, human physiology, photosynthesis for horticulture, etc.).

\end{enumerate}

