%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Weighting functions and blue light}
\label{sec:blue_light}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

**** Should we change this section to 'Rationale underpinning the selection of our recommended luminosity/weighting function with a subsubsection for blue light? ---ZM ****


It is known that short wavelength EM radiation (bluer light)
provides physiological benefits, such as
the suppression of melanopsin and 
the regulation of circadian rhythms~\citep{Pattison2018LEDphotons}.
To obtain the benefits of blue light, 
many lamps are designed with a blue spike 
in the region of 480~nm, 
the peak of the melanopsin suppression action spectrum \cite{lucas2014}.
The blue spike can be seen from the spectral power distribution~($\dot{E}_{EM,\lambda}$)
for the LED lamp in Figure~\ref{fig:wfs_and_lamps}. 

Manufacturers who design lamps with blue spikes
do not get credit for their efforts, because 
the industry-standard measure of lighting efficiency,
luminous efficacy~($K$), 
uses the photopic luminosity function~($V_\lambda$), 
which under-represents power at short wavelengths.
This state of affairs biases lighting manufacturers to reduce short wavelength
output of lamps, even when short wavelength EM radiation would 
provide physiological benefits.

To more accurately represent the utility of all wavelengths of light,
the universal luminosity function~($U_\lambda$) has been proposed 
as a replacement for the photopic luminosity function ($V_\lambda$), because it 
accounts for the sensitivity of all five types of light receptors in the human eye,
as discussed in Section~\ref{sec:human_perception_of_EM_radiation}.

Previously, 
societal exergy analysis implicitly adopted the photopic luminosity function~($V_\lambda$)
when it utilized the approximate method for calculating the exergetic efficiency of lighting.
(See Section~\ref{sec:previous_approach}.)
Thus, societal exergy analysis has, in the past, also under-represented 
the physiological benefits of blue light.

The choice of weighting function ($f_\lambda$) in societal exergy analysis
should be appropriate for the application of each lamp.

As demonstrated by Figure~\ref{fig:wfs_and_lamps}, 
which utilises the CIE 10 degree colour matching function 
provided in the \emph{ggspectra} R package \cite{Aphalo2015},
whilst the visible spectrum weighting function
preserves all light within the visible spectrum (\humaneyesensitivity), 
the human eyes perception of light and colour diminishing rapidly after $700nm$.

Therefore, to provide consistency for societal exergy analysis community moving forward,
we propose that societal exergy analysts 
adopt the universal luminosity function ($U_\lambda$) in accordance with \cite{Rea2018},
when the primary purpose of lamps is illumination.

The switch from the photopic luminosity function~($V_\lambda$)
to the universal luminosity function~($U_\lambda$) is made possible 
by the exact method described in Section~\ref{sec:framework}.
However in the absence of spectral power distribution data, 
an approximate method detailed below in Section~\ref{sec:ConversionUniversal}
must be used.


