%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsubsection{Aggregate lighting efficiencies}
\label{sec:AggEfficiencies}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

To move from the final to useful energy/exergy efficiency of a single lamp, 
to either an economy-wide or sectoral aggregate lighting efficiency, 
several types of data are required for the given period of study:

\begin{enumerate}[label={(\alph*)}]

  \item efficiency data for each lamp technology~($\eta_{E,L,v}$ and $\eta_{X,L,v}$),
  \item exergy-to-energy ratios for each of the corresponding lamp technologies~($\phi_L$), and
  \item economy-wide electricity consumption by lamp technology~($\dot{W}_{elect,1}$).

\end{enumerate}

Items (a) and (b) are rarely reported for lamps, 
nor is the associated spectral power distribution~(SPD) data.
Instead, the most common measure of lighting efficiency reported for lamps is the luminous efficacy~($K$).
Therefore, to develop an aggregate measure of lighting efficiency, 
luminous efficacy data must be converted into efficiency values.
As demonstrated in Section~\ref{sec:previous_approach} if the \emph{valuable} light
is deemed to be the radiant power weighted by the photopic luminosity function 
(luminous power, $\Phi_{pl}$),
the final to useful efficiencies are equivalent to the luminous efficiency (Equation~\ref{eq:prev_eta_X_v_light}), namely $\frac{K}{683 lm/W}$.
In the absence of SPD data a generalised exergy-to-energy ratio ($\phi_{i,pl}$) 
for each technology type must be selected,
as the shape of lamp spectral power distributions 
display relatively little variation within technology groups
compared to between groups, 
the aggregate exergy to energy ratios for those lamps also display little variation.

